<activity><title>Finding a Linear Model</title>

<introduction><p>Sea water does not freeze at exactly 32 <m>\degree</m> F because of its salinity. The temperature at which water freezes depends on its dissolved mineral content. A common unit for measuring salinity is parts per thousand, or ppt. For example, salinity of 8 ppt means 8 grams of dissolved salts in each kilogram of water. Here are some data for the freezing temperature of water.
